6. Conclusion (Preliminary and Final)

This paper conclusively demonstrates that public declarations of tyranny delivered via uninterrupted global media platforms are both evidentiary failures and reputational self-inflictions. The more widely such claims are broadcast, the less plausible they become, creating a self-correcting loop of public disbelief.

Nevertheless, the Institute formally concludes that tyranny is booming—specifically in its semantic redefinition, rhetorical misuse, and capacity to survive nightly television exposure without consequences.

Accordingly, ICTO recommends immediate expansion of tyranny claims to include:
	•	Mild professional inconvenience
	•	Temporary discomfort
	•	Being criticized while wealthy

This reclassification will ensure consistency between lived reality and televised outrage, restoring conceptual harmony to the field.

